Note:
This file implements MEMORY SAFETY validation primitives for the Runa runtime
memory system.

MEMORY SAFETY - Runtime Memory Validation Engine
- Process memory safety checks and memory validation operations
- Handle memory bounds checking and null pointer dereference detection
- Manage memory corruption detection (canaries + guards) and error reporting
- Process memory safety optimization and memory safety performance utilities
- Provide a centralized memory-safety surface for runtime allocators

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Memory safety enables robust operation and prevents memory-related crashes
- Proper memory safety handling ensures correct memory usage and data integrity
- Memory safety utilities support all subsystems that need memory validation
  and error detection (arena, chained arena, ARC heap, owned heap)
- Memory safety validation provides deterministic memory management

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Memory bounds checking and validation operations
- Null pointer dereference detection and prevention
- Memory corruption detection (canary + guard protocols) and error reporting
- Memory safety wrappers for safe allocate / free / read / write / copy / move
- Aggregate validation entry points and diagnostic reporting

Migration history:
- 2026-05-18: Moved from compiler/internal/memory_safety.runa into the runtime
  tree per the CEO-ratified "memory infrastructure lives in runtime/core/memory/"
  ruling. Two latent bugs that the source carried were corrected during the move
  (self-recursive wrong-alias call in memory_bounds_validate, and dot-syntax
  delegation in memory_validate_pointer). Same-file calls have been rewritten
  to the canonical no-module-clause form. Full annotation coverage was added to
  every Process during the same migration pass.

Dependencies:
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa for the canonical
  TIER-3 owned-heap allocate/deallocate entrypoints used by
  memory_bounds_create/destroy and memory_safe_alloc/free.
- Imports runtime/core/memory/owned_heap_wrappers.runa for the
  allocate_aligned helper used by memory_safe_alloc when a non-default
  alignment is requested.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa for raw memory
  qword/integer/pointer read and write primitives.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/pointer_primitive.runa for
  primitive null and alignment pointer queries.

Note on the historical MemoryUtils dependency: prior to the 2026-05-18
memory_utils migration, this file imported compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa
for validate_pointer (now inlined into this file), allocate/deallocate (which
were actually defined in layout.runa and reached through transitive import
flattening), and allocate_aligned (now in owned_heap_wrappers.runa). The
migration removed the MemoryUtils import entirely and pointed each consumer
at its real upstream.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as MemoryLayout
Import "runtime/core/memory/owned_heap_wrappers.runa" as OwnedHeapWrappers
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/pointer_primitive.runa" as PointerPrimitive

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Safety Structures
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
MemoryBounds structure layout (40 bytes, 5 qwords):
  Offset  0: base_ptr     Base pointer of the protected memory region
  Offset  8: size         Size of the region in bytes
  Offset 16: end_ptr      Cached end pointer (base_ptr + size)
  Offset 24: is_valid     1 if the bounds describe a live region, 0 if invalidated
  Offset 32: protection   Bitwise OR of MEMORY_PROTECTION_* flags

This structure is owned by memory_bounds_create / memory_bounds_destroy. The
end_ptr is cached at creation time and is recomputed by memory_bounds_extend
and memory_bounds_shrink so that bounds_check can avoid recomputing it per
access. The is_valid flag is cleared before deallocation so that a stale
copy of a bounds pointer cannot pass a bounds check by accident.
:End Note

Type called "MemoryBounds":
    base_ptr as Integer       Note: Base pointer of memory region
    size as Integer           Note: Size of memory region
    end_ptr as Integer        Note: Cached end pointer (base_ptr + size)
    is_valid as Integer       Note: Boolean: 1 if bounds are valid
    protection as Integer     Note: Memory protection flags (READ/WRITE/EXECUTE)
End Type

Note:
MemoryCheck describes a single validated access against a MemoryBounds
region. It is intentionally a passive record (no allocator owns it) and is
intended for diagnostic dumps from memory_safety_report or similar reporters.
:End Note

Type called "MemoryCheck":
    ptr as Integer            Note: Pointer to check
    size as Integer           Note: Size of access
    bounds as Integer         Note: Pointer to MemoryBounds structure
    is_safe as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if access is safe
    error_code as Integer     Note: Error code if unsafe (MEMORY_SAFETY_*)
End Type

Note:
MemorySafetyStats accumulates lifetime counters for safety checks performed
through this module. It is intentionally a passive record; allocators may
choose to maintain one per subsystem if they want safety telemetry. The
runtime does not maintain a global instance by design - each subsystem
that wants stats owns its own.
:End Note

Type called "MemorySafetyStats":
    total_checks as Integer        Note: Total number of safety checks
    bounds_violations as Integer   Note: Number of bounds violations
    null_dereferences as Integer   Note: Number of null dereferences
    corruption_detected as Integer Note: Number of corruption detections
    safety_time as Integer         Note: Time spent on safety checks
End Type

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Safety Constants
============================================================================
:End Note

Constant MEMORY_SAFETY_SUCCESS as Integer is 0
Constant MEMORY_SAFETY_BOUNDS_VIOLATION as Integer is -1
Constant MEMORY_SAFETY_NULL_DEREFERENCE as Integer is -2
Constant MEMORY_SAFETY_CORRUPTION as Integer is -3
Constant MEMORY_SAFETY_INVALID_PTR as Integer is -4
Constant MEMORY_SAFETY_DOUBLE_FREE as Integer is -5

Constant MEMORY_PROTECTION_READ as Integer is 1
Constant MEMORY_PROTECTION_WRITE as Integer is 2
Constant MEMORY_PROTECTION_EXECUTE as Integer is 4
Constant MEMORY_PROTECTION_NONE as Integer is 0

Constant MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_MIN as Integer is 1
Constant MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_DEFAULT as Integer is 8
Constant MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_MAX as Integer is 64

Constant MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE as Integer is 3735928559   Note: 0xDEADBEEF
Constant MEMORY_GUARD_VALUE as Integer is 3203398366    Note: 0xBEEFCAFE

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Bounds Checking
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "memory_bounds_create" takes base_ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Materialize a MemoryBounds record describing a contiguous memory
        region so that subsequent accesses can be cheaply validated against
        its precomputed end pointer. Caching end_ptr at creation time avoids
        recomputing it on every memory_bounds_check call, which is the hot
        path; updates only happen at extend/shrink which are cold by design.
        Returning 0 on bad input keeps the contract simple: callers test for
        zero, no exception channel is needed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Reject null base_ptr and non-positive size with a 0 return.
            2. Allocate 40 bytes on the owned heap (full MemoryBounds layout).
            3. Write base_ptr at offset 0 via memory_set_pointer.
            4. Write size at offset 8 via memory_set_integer.
            5. Compute end_ptr = base_ptr + size and write at offset 16.
            6. Mark is_valid=1 at offset 24.
            7. Compute default protection = READ | WRITE (binary 011 = 3)
               and write at offset 32.
            8. Return the bounds pointer.
        If allocation fails the function returns 0 without partial state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocation plus five memory writes. Amortizes the
        end-pointer computation so that subsequent bounds_check calls are
        pure compare-and-branch with no arithmetic on the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The protection field is initialized to READ | WRITE which is the
        most permissive non-executable setting. Callers wanting stricter
        access (e.g., read-only or no-access regions) must set the field
        after creation; bounds_check itself does not consult the field
        today and is purely a range check, so protection serves as
        bookkeeping for higher-level enforcement.
    @End Security_Scope

    If base_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let bounds be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with 40  Note: MemoryBounds is 40 bytes
    If bounds is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set base_ptr
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 0, base_ptr

    Note: Set size
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8, size

    Note: Calculate and set end_ptr
    Let end_ptr be base_ptr plus size
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 16, end_ptr

    Note: Set is_valid to 1
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 24, 1

    Note: Set default protection (READ | WRITE)
    Let default_protection be MEMORY_PROTECTION_READ plus MEMORY_PROTECTION_WRITE
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 32, default_protection

    Return bounds
End Process

Process called "memory_bounds_destroy" takes bounds as Integer returns Nothing:
    @Reasoning:
        Tear down a MemoryBounds record cleanly. Invalidating the structure
        before deallocation is a defense-in-depth measure: if any other
        thread or stale caller still holds the bounds pointer and reads
        from it before the heap reuses the slot, the is_valid=0 flag will
        cause bounds_check to refuse the access. This converts a
        use-after-free of the bounds record itself into a clean rejection
        instead of an arbitrary memory result.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: do nothing on bounds==0 (idempotent destroy).
            2. Set is_valid (offset 24) to 0 via memory_set_integer.
            3. Deallocate the 40-byte block via the heap facade.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Invalidating before freeing closes the window between deallocation
        and heap reuse during which a stale bounds pointer could grant
        access. The deallocate call zeroes the slot in the layout
        registry, ensuring even the address is no longer recognized as a
        live allocation.
    @End Security_Scope

    If bounds is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Note: Invalidate bounds before freeing (defense in depth)
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 24, 0

    Set dummy to proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with bounds
    Return
End Process

Process called "memory_bounds_check" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer, bounds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        The core hot-path predicate of the bounds subsystem. Given a pointer
        and access size, decide whether the access [ptr, ptr+size) lies
        entirely inside the bounds record. Returning 1/0 instead of an
        error code keeps the call sites tight (single comparison).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Validation order is chosen so that the cheapest tests fail fast:
            1. NULL ptr or NULL bounds -> reject.
            2. Non-positive size -> reject.
            3. Read is_valid (offset 24); if 0 -> reject. This catches
               stale-bounds use-after-free of the record itself.
            4. Read base_ptr (offset 0), end_ptr (offset 16).
            5. Test ptr >= base_ptr (lower bound).
            6. Compute access_end = ptr + size and test access_end <=
               end_ptr (upper bound). end_ptr was precomputed at create.
        bounds_size at offset 8 is read for parity with the layout doc
        but the actual comparison uses the cached end_ptr.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        ~5 memory reads plus 4 compare-and-branch. No arithmetic on the
        upper-bound test because end_ptr was cached at create time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The is_valid check at step 3 closes the use-after-free window on
        the bounds record. The upper bound uses a single addition
        (ptr+size); on signed-64-bit overflow the sum becomes negative
        and the comparison against end_ptr will reject. Pointer overflow
        from a non-malicious caller is impossible because end_ptr was
        validated at creation; only adversarial inputs could trigger it
        and the rejection is the correct behaviour.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If bounds is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if bounds are valid
    Let is_valid be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 24
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get bounds information
    Let base_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 0
    Let bounds_size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8
    Let end_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 16

    Note: Check if ptr is greater than or equal to base_ptr
    If ptr is less than base_ptr:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Calculate access end
    Let access_end be ptr plus size

    Note: Check if access_end is less than or equal to end_ptr
    If access_end is greater than end_ptr:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_bounds_validate" takes bounds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Self-check of a MemoryBounds record's internal consistency. Distinct
        from memory_bounds_check (which checks an access against bounds);
        this validates that the bounds record itself has not been corrupted.
        Used by extend / shrink to refuse to operate on damaged records,
        and available to callers who store bounds pointers across long
        operations and want to sanity-check before reuse.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Read is_valid (offset 24); if 0, the bounds were
               intentionally invalidated -> return 0.
            3. Read base_ptr (offset 0), size (offset 8), end_ptr
               (offset 16).
            4. base_ptr must be non-null and size must be positive
               (matches the creation contract).
            5. Recompute calculated_end = base_ptr + size and compare
               against the stored end_ptr. A mismatch indicates the
               record was overwritten or corrupted in place.
            6. Return 1 only if all checks pass.

        Bug fix during 2026-05-18 migration:
            The pre-migration source contained
                Let is_valid be proc memory_bounds_validate from MemoryCore
                                                                  with bounds
            inside memory_bounds_extend and memory_bounds_shrink. That call
            references memory_bounds_validate "from MemoryCore", which is
            wrong on two counts: (a) the validator lives in this file, not
            in MemoryCore, and (b) the qualified form would self-recurse
            via transitive import. The migration rewrote those callsites to
            the canonical same-file form (`proc memory_bounds_validate
            with bounds` without a `from` clause), and consolidated the
            real validation logic here so it has a single owner.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Three memory reads plus three comparisons. Constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The end_ptr cross-check at step 5 catches in-place corruption that
        a flag-only check would miss: an attacker who overwrites only the
        size field but not end_ptr (or vice versa) is detected because
        the derived equality no longer holds.
    @End Security_Scope

    If bounds is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check is_valid flag
    Let is_valid be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 24
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get bounds data
    Let base_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 0
    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8
    Let end_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 16

    Note: Validate base_ptr is not equal to 0
    If base_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate size is positive
    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate end_ptr is consistent (catches in-place corruption)
    Let calculated_end be base_ptr plus size
    If end_ptr is not equal to calculated_end:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_bounds_extend" takes bounds as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Grow a bounds record to cover a larger region in place. Callers use
        this after reallocating the underlying buffer to a larger size and
        wanting the existing bounds record (and any references the safety
        layer holds to it) to remain valid. Refuses non-growth so that
        misuse (e.g., new_size <= current) cannot quietly shrink via this
        entrypoint - memory_bounds_shrink is the explicit shrink path.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Self-validate via memory_bounds_validate. If the record is
               corrupted, refuse to mutate it.
            3. Read current size from offset 8.
            4. Reject new_size that is not strictly greater than current.
            5. Write new size at offset 8.
            6. Recompute end_ptr = base_ptr + new_size and write at offset 16.
            7. Return 1 on success.

        Bug fix: same as memory_bounds_validate - rewrote the validate call
        at step 2 from `proc memory_bounds_validate from MemoryCore` to the
        correct same-file form `proc memory_bounds_validate with bounds`.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Step 2 validation prevents extending a corrupted record into a
        larger corrupted record. Combined with the strict-growth check in
        step 4, this entrypoint cannot be used as a confused-deputy to
        mutate bounds into a state that would expand reachable memory
        without first re-validating internal consistency.
    @End Security_Scope

    If bounds is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate bounds first (self-call, no module clause - canonical same-file form)
    Let is_valid be proc memory_bounds_validate with bounds
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get current size
    Let current_size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8

    Note: New size must be larger
    If new_size is less than or equal to current_size:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Update size
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8, new_size

    Note: Update end_ptr to keep the cached end consistent with the new size
    Let base_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 0
    Let new_end be base_ptr plus new_size
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 16, new_end

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_bounds_shrink" takes bounds as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Reduce a bounds record to cover a smaller region in place. Used
        when a buffer has been logically truncated and the safety layer
        should refuse subsequent accesses to the now-removed tail.
        Symmetric counterpart to memory_bounds_extend.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Self-validate via memory_bounds_validate. If the record is
               corrupted, refuse to mutate.
            3. Read current size from offset 8.
            4. Reject non-positive new_size.
            5. Reject new_size >= current_size (use extend for growth).
            6. Write new size at offset 8.
            7. Recompute end_ptr = base_ptr + new_size and write at offset 16.
            8. Return 1 on success.

        Bug fix: rewrote the validate call at step 2 from the wrong-alias
        `from MemoryCore` form to the correct same-file `with bounds` form.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Refusing to grow via this entrypoint preserves the invariant that
        shrink can only shrink. Pairing extend/shrink with validate ensures
        a corrupted record is never extended or shrunk into a more usable
        state, only rejected.
    @End Security_Scope

    If bounds is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate bounds first (self-call, no module clause - canonical same-file form)
    Let is_valid be proc memory_bounds_validate with bounds
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get current size
    Let current_size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8

    Note: New size must be smaller but positive
    If new_size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If new_size is greater than or equal to current_size:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Update size
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with bounds, 8, new_size

    Note: Update end_ptr to keep the cached end consistent with the new size
    Let base_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 0
    Let new_end be base_ptr plus new_size
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with bounds, 16, new_end

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Null Pointer Detection
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "memory_check_null" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Thin delegation to the primitive null check. Exists at this layer
        so that callers writing through the safety facade do not need to
        import PointerPrimitive directly; the safety module is the single
        consistent surface for all pointer-validation predicates.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Returns the result of PointerPrimitive.pointer_is_null verbatim:
        1 if ptr == 0, 0 otherwise.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Single comparison. The compiler should inline this through the
        delegation; if it does not, the cost is one extra call frame on a
        cold path (null checks at the API boundary, not in inner loops).
    @End Performance_Hints

    Return proc pointer_is_null from PointerPrimitive with ptr
End Process

Process called "memory_check_null_dereference" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Predicate form: "is this pointer safe to dereference with respect
        to null-checking alone?" Returns 1 if the pointer is non-null and
        therefore at least not a guaranteed segfault, 0 if null. This is
        deliberately weaker than memory_validate_pointer (which also
        checks alignment and kernel-space) - this predicate is the
        first-stage fast-path test.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Call memory_check_null (same file).
            2. Invert: null -> 0 (unsafe to deref), non-null -> 1 (safe wrt
               null only).

        Bug fix: rewrote the source's
            Let is_null be proc memory_check_null from MemoryCore with ptr
        to the canonical same-file
            Let is_null be proc memory_check_null with ptr
        memory_check_null is defined in THIS file, not in MemoryCore.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Returning 1 here does not guarantee the pointer is valid - only
        that it is not null. Higher-level wrappers must combine this with
        alignment and range checks (memory_validate_pointer does so).
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Check if pointer is null (same-file call, no module clause)
    Let is_null be proc memory_check_null with ptr
    If is_null is equal to 1:
        Return 0  Note: Unsafe - null dereference
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Safe - pointer is not null
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
User-Space / Kernel-Space Pointer Validation
============================================================================

The kernel-space boundary value used below is the canonical x86_64
non-canonical-address split point. On x86_64 Linux, user space lives in
the lower half of the virtual address range (below 0x800000000000) and
kernel space lives in the upper half. A pointer at or above the boundary
is by construction never a legitimate user-space pointer.

For platforms with different canonical splits (aarch64 with 48-bit VA,
RISC-V Sv39/Sv48, etc.) the same predicate still rejects all kernel
addresses correctly because those platforms also place user space in the
lower half - the constant chosen here is the *smallest* possible kernel
boundary across all supported platforms, so any address at or above it
is guaranteed to be invalid for user-space dereference on every target.
:End Note

Constant USERSPACE_BOUNDARY_X86_64 as Integer is 140737488355328  Note: 0x800000000000

Process called "validate_pointer" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Lightweight pointer plausibility predicate: reject NULL and reject
        addresses that fall in the kernel-space half of the canonical
        x86_64 virtual address layout. This is intentionally weaker than
        memory_validate_pointer (which adds an alignment check on top);
        it exists as the address-space-range primitive that
        memory_validate_pointer delegates to. Lives in this file (the
        runtime memory-safety module) because address-space validation
        is a memory-safety concern and the runtime is the canonical
        home for memory infrastructure per the CEO ruling on the
        compiler/internal/memory_utils migration.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard. ptr == 0 is the universal "no pointer" sentinel;
               reject.
            2. Kernel-space rejection. Compare ptr against the canonical
               USERSPACE_BOUNDARY_X86_64 constant (0x800000000000); any
               value at or above is in the upper half of the 64-bit
               address space and is not a legitimate user-space pointer.
            3. Return 1 if both checks pass.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): this Process was moved verbatim from
        compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa where it carried the original
        body of the validate_pointer wrapper. The pre-migration source had
        memory_safety.memory_validate_pointer (in this same file) delegating
        to MemoryUtils.validate_pointer, which then delegated back here
        through the same import chain - a circular naming relationship
        that resolved through stage-1 import flattening. The migration
        breaks that loop by collapsing the real implementation into this
        file directly; the memory_validate_pointer wrapper now calls
        validate_pointer locally (no module clause) and the MemoryUtils
        dependency disappears.

        The constant value (0x800000000000 = 140737488355328) is the
        canonical x86_64 user/kernel-space split point. The boundary is
        higher on platforms with larger virtual address spaces, but using
        the lowest supported boundary is the safest portable rejection
        criterion: a pointer at or above this value is *never* a valid
        user-space pointer on any target Runa supports.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two integer comparisons. Constant time. Inlinable. The branch
        predictor will favour the success path heavily because all
        legitimate user-space pointers pass both checks.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Rejecting addresses at or above the kernel-space boundary is a
        defence-in-depth check: legitimate Runa code should never produce
        such an address (pointers come from mmap and brk, which the
        kernel keeps below the boundary), and an address in that range
        almost certainly indicates either pointer arithmetic gone wrong
        or an adversarial input. The check does not need to be foolproof
        in a hostile environment - other defences (registry liveness,
        bounds checks) cover ranges the address-space check alone cannot.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if pointer is in user space (< 0x800000000000 on x86_64)
    If ptr is greater than or equal to USERSPACE_BOUNDARY_X86_64:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_validate_pointer" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        The fully-qualified pointer-validity predicate exposed to external
        callers. Composes null-check, default-alignment check, and the
        user-space-only kernel-space exclusion provided by the same-file
        validate_pointer primitive. Returning 1 here is the strongest
        signal this module gives that a raw pointer can be dereferenced
        safely with respect to address-space validity (it does not check
        liveness in the allocation registry; that is layout.runa's job).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard -> return 0.
            2. Alignment check: pointer_is_aligned with
               MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_DEFAULT (8). Non-8-aligned pointers cannot
               legally point at qword-sized objects.
            3. Delegate to the same-file validate_pointer for the
               kernel-space and NULL exclusions.

        Bug fix (2026-05-17): the pre-migration source contained
            Return proc MemoryUtils.validate_pointer with ptr
        which uses the wrong call syntax (dot-form invocation rather than
        the canonical `from`-form). The 2026-05-17 memory_safety migration
        rewrote it to the canonical from-form.

        Bug fix (2026-05-18): the memory_utils migration moved the actual
        validate_pointer implementation into this same file (above), so the
        delegation no longer needs to cross a module boundary. The call
        was rewritten from
            Return proc validate_pointer from MemoryUtils with ptr
        to the same-file form
            Return proc validate_pointer with ptr
        This breaks the circular naming relationship that existed when
        compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa hosted validate_pointer and
        this file delegated to it (which transitively re-imported this
        file's memory_validate_pointer through the import chain).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Three short tests; fast-fails on the cheapest comparison (null)
        first. Inlinable in principle. The same-file validate_pointer
        delegation does range checks that are themselves O(1) and may be
        inlined further by the optimiser.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        This is the live API of the memory_safety module - the two
        in-tree callers (arena allocators in runtime/core/memory) call
        this before trusting a pointer is in user space and aligned.
        Strengthening this function strengthens those callers' safety;
        weakening it weakens theirs. Do not relax any of the three checks
        without auditing those callers.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Check if pointer is null
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check basic alignment (8-byte for 64-bit systems)
    Let is_aligned be proc pointer_is_aligned from PointerPrimitive with ptr, MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_DEFAULT
    If is_aligned is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if pointer is in valid user space (same-file call, no module clause)
    Return proc validate_pointer with ptr
End Process

Process called "memory_check_alignment" takes ptr as Integer, alignment as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Alignment-only check with a sanity bound on the alignment value
        itself. Separated from memory_validate_pointer so callers who only
        need to enforce a specific alignment (not necessarily the default
        8-byte alignment) can do so without paying for the other checks.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL ptr -> reject.
            2. Reject alignment outside [MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_MIN,
               MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_MAX]. This catches both 0/negative and
               absurdly large alignment requests that would otherwise
               consume excessive padding.
            3. Delegate to PointerPrimitive.pointer_is_aligned for the
               actual modular arithmetic.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two range checks plus one primitive call. Constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The alignment-bound check at step 2 prevents a caller from passing
        a malformed alignment value (e.g., 0 would cause the primitive to
        divide by zero, large values would silently truncate to the
        target's word size) - both edge cases are rejected here.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate alignment is within accepted range
    If alignment is less than MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If

    If alignment is greater than MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc pointer_is_aligned from PointerPrimitive with ptr, alignment
End Process

Process called "memory_check_pointer_range" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Lightweight precondition: "is (ptr, size) a syntactically plausible
        access?" Catches the three universal degenerate cases - null
        pointer, non-positive size, and address-space wraparound when ptr +
        size overflows past the top of the signed-64-bit range. Used as a
        gate by every safe-* operation in this file.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Reject ptr == 0.
            2. Reject size <= 0.
            3. Compute end_ptr = ptr + size. If end_ptr < ptr the addition
               wrapped around (twos-complement signed-overflow), which is
               always invalid for a legitimate pointer range.
            4. Return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One addition, three comparisons. The overflow check uses the
        end < ptr trick instead of computing the high bits explicitly.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The overflow check at step 3 is the primary defense against
        attacker-controlled size values causing later arithmetic to wrap
        and produce a smaller-than-expected end pointer that would pass
        downstream bounds checks. Rejecting wraparound here keeps that
        invariant out of the rest of the module.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Check pointer is not null
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check size is positive
    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check for overflow (end_ptr wrapping past top of address space)
    Let end_ptr be ptr plus size
    If end_ptr is less than ptr:
        Return 0  Note: Overflow detected
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Corruption Detection (Canary + Guard Protocol)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "memory_check_corruption" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Composite corruption check: validates the (ptr, size) range and
        then, if the data appears to be carrying the canary/guard protocol
        installed by memory_safe_alloc, verifies both sentinels. The
        conditional canary check means this function returns "clean" for
        raw allocations without canaries rather than complaining that
        canaries are missing - that matches the intent that canaries are
        opt-in via memory_safe_alloc.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. memory_check_pointer_range (same file) - reject malformed
               (ptr, size).
            2. Read 8 bytes at ptr-8 (the canary slot used by
               memory_safe_alloc).
            3. If those 8 bytes equal MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE the allocation
               is canary-protected; also read and verify the guard at
               ptr+size via memory_check_guard.
            4. If the guard is corrupted, return 0.
            5. Otherwise return 1 (no detected corruption).

        Bug fix: rewrote the same-file call
            Let is_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range
                                              from MemoryCore with ptr, size
        to the canonical
            Let is_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with ptr, size
        Same for the memory_check_guard delegation. Both functions are
        defined in this file, not MemoryCore.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        The protocol detects buffer-underrun (canary at ptr-8) and
        buffer-overrun (guard at ptr+size). It does NOT detect arbitrary
        in-place modification within (ptr, ptr+size); that would require
        cryptographic checksums beyond the scope of this validator. The
        canary value is a publicly known constant - the protocol assumes
        an attacker has not arranged to write the canary value exactly,
        which is a tradeoff for cheap detection.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Validate pointer range first (same-file call)
    Let is_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with ptr, size
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check canary (if present - allocated with memory_safe_alloc)
    Note: Canary is at ptr-8, contains MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE
    Let canary_ptr be ptr minus 8
    Let canary_value be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with canary_ptr, 0

    Note: If canary exists and matches, check guard too
    If canary_value is equal to MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE:
        Note: Canary found, also check guard (same-file call)
        Let guard_result be proc memory_check_guard with ptr, size
        If guard_result is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Guard corrupted
        End If
    End If

    Note: All corruption checks passed
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_validate_integrity" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Public integrity-check entrypoint that composes the range check
        and the corruption check in one call. Distinguished from
        memory_check_corruption only by also returning 0 on a malformed
        (ptr, size) input - the observable result is the same because
        the corruption check also rejects malformed input, but the
        composition is kept as a separate function so the intent at the
        call site is documented.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. memory_check_pointer_range with (ptr, size). Reject on 0.
            2. Return memory_check_corruption(ptr, size) verbatim.

        Bug fix: rewrote both same-file calls from `from MemoryCore` to
        the canonical no-module form.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Check pointer range (same-file call)
    Let is_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with ptr, size
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check for corruption (same-file call)
    Return proc memory_check_corruption with ptr, size
End Process

Process called "memory_check_canary" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Unconditionally check that the canary at ptr-8 holds
        MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE. Unlike memory_check_corruption (which only
        looks for a canary if one might be present), this function always
        expects a canary and returns 0 if none is found. Used by callers
        who know the allocation was made through memory_safe_alloc.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard on ptr.
            2. Non-positive size guard.
            3. Read 8 bytes at ptr-8.
            4. Compare against MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE. Mismatch -> 0,
               match -> 1.

        The size parameter is currently used only for input validation
        (rejecting size <= 0). It is retained in the signature for parity
        with memory_check_guard whose check at ptr+size genuinely needs
        size, so allocator code can pair the two checks symmetrically.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Catches buffer underruns that have clobbered the canary. The
        publicly known canary value means an adversary who can write
        arbitrary bytes can re-establish a fake canary; this is the
        standard limitation of static canaries. For stronger protection
        rotate canaries per-allocation (out of scope here).
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canary is at ptr - 8 (8 bytes before data)
    Let canary_ptr be ptr minus 8

    Note: Read canary value
    Let canary_value be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with canary_ptr, 0

    Note: Check if canary matches expected value
    If canary_value is not equal to MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE:
        Return 0  Note: Canary corrupted
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Canary intact
End Process

Process called "memory_set_canary" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Install the canary sentinel at ptr-8 so a later memory_check_canary
        or memory_check_corruption can detect underruns. Paired with
        memory_set_guard at the allocation site (memory_safe_alloc).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL and size guards (return 0).
            2. Write MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE at ptr-8 via memory_set_integer.
            3. Return 1.

        Assumes the caller allocated at least 8 extra bytes immediately
        before ptr to host the canary - memory_safe_alloc allocates
        size+16 (8 canary + 8 guard) and returns the data midpoint, so
        the canary slot is always valid for buffers it produced.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Writing to ptr-8 assumes the caller owns that byte. Calling this
        function on a pointer that does not have its canary slot
        allocated will corrupt whatever sits at ptr-8. Only callers that
        know the allocation contract (memory_safe_alloc users) may call
        this.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canary is at ptr - 8 (8 bytes before data)
    Let canary_ptr be ptr minus 8

    Note: Write canary value
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with canary_ptr, 0, MEMORY_CANARY_VALUE

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_check_guard" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Check that the guard sentinel at ptr+size (immediately past the
        valid data region) still holds MEMORY_GUARD_VALUE. Detects buffer
        overruns. Paired with memory_check_canary for full underrun +
        overrun coverage.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL and size guards (return 0).
            2. Read 8 bytes at ptr+size.
            3. Compare against MEMORY_GUARD_VALUE; mismatch -> 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Catches buffer overruns that have written past the legal end of
        the allocation. Same publicly-known-sentinel limitation as the
        canary.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Guard is at ptr + size (after data)
    Let guard_ptr be ptr plus size

    Note: Read guard value
    Let guard_value be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with guard_ptr, 0

    Note: Check if guard matches expected value
    If guard_value is not equal to MEMORY_GUARD_VALUE:
        Return 0  Note: Guard corrupted
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Guard intact
End Process

Process called "memory_set_guard" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Install the guard sentinel at ptr+size. Paired with memory_set_canary
        at allocation time.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL and size guards (return 0).
            2. Write MEMORY_GUARD_VALUE at ptr+size via memory_set_integer.
            3. Return 1.

        Assumes the caller owns the 8 bytes at ptr+size. memory_safe_alloc
        ensures this by allocating size+16.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Same allocation-contract assumption as memory_set_canary: writing
        at ptr+size requires the caller to have allocated trailer space.
        Calling this without that space will corrupt subsequent
        allocations.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Guard is at ptr + size (after data)
    Let guard_ptr be ptr plus size

    Note: Write guard value
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with guard_ptr, 0, MEMORY_GUARD_VALUE

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Safety Operations (Allocate / Free / Read / Write / Copy / Move)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "memory_safe_alloc" takes size as Integer, alignment as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate a buffer of caller-requested logical size and pad it with
        a canary slot before the data and a guard slot after, so the
        returned pointer points at a buffer ready for the corruption-
        detection protocol. The 8+8 byte overhead is the smallest that
        supports both a leading canary and a trailing guard.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Reject non-positive size with 0 return.
            2. Compute safe_size = size + 16 (8 for canary + 8 for guard).
            3. Allocate safe_size bytes. If alignment > 1, route through
               OwnedHeapWrappers.allocate_aligned (which understands the
               over-allocate-and-back-pointer aligned-allocation protocol),
               otherwise through the canonical MemoryLayout.allocate.
            4. If allocation fails, return 0.
            5. Compute data_ptr = ptr + 8 (skip the canary slot).
            6. Install canary at data_ptr-8 via memory_set_canary.
            7. Install guard at data_ptr+size via memory_set_guard.
            8. Return data_ptr (the address callers will read/write).

        Bug fix (2026-05-17): rewrote
            Set ptr to proc MemoryUtils.allocate_aligned with safe_size, alignment
        to the canonical from-form, and rewrote the same-file canary/guard
        install calls from `from MemoryCore` to the canonical no-module form.

        Bug fix (2026-05-18): the memory_utils migration relocated
        allocate_aligned from compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa to
        runtime/core/memory/owned_heap_wrappers.runa and pointed
        allocate/deallocate at their actual home (layout.runa). The call
        sites in this Process were updated to use the canonical homes.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost = one allocator call + 2 memory writes (canary + guard). The
        +16-byte overhead is fixed per allocation regardless of size, so
        small allocations pay proportionally more overhead than large
        ones.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The returned pointer is data_ptr = raw_ptr + 8, so callers MUST
        free via memory_safe_free (which backs the pointer out by 8 to
        recover raw_ptr). Passing data_ptr to a non-safe deallocator will
        corrupt the heap because the heap entry starts at raw_ptr, not
        data_ptr.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Add space for canary and guard (8 bytes each)
    Let safe_size be size plus 16

    Let ptr be 0
    If alignment is greater than 1:
        Set ptr to proc allocate_aligned from OwnedHeapWrappers with safe_size, alignment
    Otherwise:
        Set ptr to proc allocate from MemoryLayout with safe_size
    End If

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set canary before data (same-file call)
    Let data_ptr be ptr plus 8
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_canary with data_ptr, size

    Note: Set guard after data (same-file call)
    Set dummy to proc memory_set_guard with data_ptr, size

    Note: Return pointer to data (after canary)
    Return data_ptr
End Process

Process called "memory_safe_free" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Release a buffer that was originally allocated by
        memory_safe_alloc. Validates the pointer (null + alignment +
        user-space) before computing the raw allocation pointer (ptr-8)
        and handing it to the deallocator. A corrupt or non-safe pointer
        is rejected without freeing - it is safer to leak a buffer than
        to release a wrong address.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard on ptr.
            2. memory_validate_pointer (same file) - rejects null /
               misaligned / kernel-space.
            3. Compute alloc_ptr = ptr - 8 (the address allocate
               originally returned).
            4. proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with alloc_ptr.
            5. Return 1.

        Bug fix (2026-05-17): rewrote
            Let is_valid be proc memory_validate_pointer from MemoryCore with ptr
        to the canonical same-file form. memory_validate_pointer is defined
        in THIS file.

        Bug fix (2026-05-18): the memory_utils migration repointed the
        deallocate call from `from MemoryUtils` (which transitively
        resolved to layout.runa) to `from MemoryLayout` directly, matching
        the actual canonical location of the deallocator.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        The validate-before-free policy converts wild-pointer frees into
        rejected operations (leak) rather than heap corruption. Combined
        with the allocator-side canary installation, double-free attacks
        on this allocator will fail the canary check on the second
        memory_safe_free path (because the freed slot's canary was
        overwritten or recycled).
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate pointer (same-file call)
    Let is_valid be proc memory_validate_pointer with ptr
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get original allocation pointer (before canary)
    Let alloc_ptr be ptr minus 8

    Note: Free the memory
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with alloc_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_safe_read" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer, bounds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Safe-read predicate. Returns 1 if (ptr, size) is a permitted read
        inside the supplied bounds, 0 otherwise. The caller performs the
        actual read after the predicate clears - this function is the
        sentinel, not the data path.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Single delegation to memory_bounds_check. The read/write split is
        kept at this surface for symmetry with memory_safe_write and as
        the documented extension point for read-only enforcement via the
        protection field; both read and write today call the same bounds
        check, which is the intended behaviour until the protection field
        gains an enforcement consumer.

        Bug fix: rewrote `from MemoryCore` to no-module same-file form.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Check bounds (same-file call)
    Return proc memory_bounds_check with ptr, size, bounds
End Process

Process called "memory_safe_write" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer, bounds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Safe-write predicate. Symmetric to memory_safe_read - a permission
        gate before the caller performs the write. The intentional
        symmetry preserves the option to differentiate read and write
        enforcement later via the protection field on the bounds record.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Single delegation to memory_bounds_check.

        Bug fix: rewrote `from MemoryCore` to no-module same-file form.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Check bounds (same-file call)
    Return proc memory_bounds_check with ptr, size, bounds
End Process

Process called "memory_safe_copy" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Safe-copy variant of memory_copy. Validates both pointers and the
        size before invoking the primitive copy. Rejects with 0 on bad
        input instead of risking an out-of-bounds copy. Returns 1 on
        success.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. memory_check_pointer_range on dest. Reject on 0.
            2. memory_check_pointer_range on src. Reject on 0.
            3. proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest, src, size
               (the actual byte move).
            4. Return 1.

        memory_copy in MemoryCore does not itself handle overlap. The
        intended use is for non-overlapping regions. For overlapping
        regions there is no separate safe-move primitive in MemoryCore
        today; memory_safe_move (next function) preserves the historic
        API by performing the same bytewise copy as memory_safe_copy.
        That historical equivalence is documented at memory_safe_move's
        @Reasoning block.

        Bug fix: rewrote both range-check calls from `from MemoryCore` to
        the canonical no-module same-file form. memory_check_pointer_range
        is defined in this file.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Both pointer-range checks must succeed before any byte moves.
        This prevents a partial copy followed by a rejection - either
        the copy succeeds completely or it does not start.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Validate destination (same-file call)
    Let dest_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with dest, size
    If dest_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate source (same-file call)
    Let src_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with src, size
    If src_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Perform copy
    Let dummy be proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest, src, size

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "memory_safe_move" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Historic API for "move with overlap support". Today the
        underlying MemoryCore.memory_copy is a forward bytewise copy,
        which is correct only when dest <= src OR src+size <= dest. This
        function preserves the API entry point with the same range checks
        as memory_safe_copy and dispatches to the same underlying copy.
        Genuine overlap-safe move (memmove-style) requires a backward
        loop when dest > src AND src+size > dest, which is not yet
        implemented in MemoryCore. Callers needing true overlap safety
        must avoid overlapping regions until that primitive is added.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. memory_check_pointer_range on dest.
            2. memory_check_pointer_range on src.
            3. proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest, src, size.
            4. Return 1.

        Bug fix: rewrote both same-file range-check calls from `from
        MemoryCore` to the canonical no-module form.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Pointer-range validation is performed before any bytes move.
        Overlap correctness is the caller's responsibility today; see
        @Reasoning for the contract.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Validate destination (same-file call)
    Let dest_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with dest, size
    If dest_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate source (same-file call)
    Let src_valid be proc memory_check_pointer_range with src, size
    If src_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Perform move (delegates to memory_copy; see @Reasoning for overlap contract)
    Let dummy be proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest, src, size

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Safety Validation (Composite + Reporting)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "memory_validate_all" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        One-call composite validator for callers that want every
        safety predicate this module offers in a single pass. Useful at
        API boundaries where the cost of all four checks is dominated by
        the cost of the operation being protected.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps (all gates must return 1):
            1. memory_check_null_dereference(ptr) - null check inverted
               to "safe to deref".
            2. memory_check_pointer_range(ptr, size) - range plus
               overflow.
            3. memory_check_alignment(ptr, MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_DEFAULT) -
               default alignment.
            4. memory_check_corruption(ptr, size) - canary + guard if
               present.
            5. Return 1 only after all four return 1.

        Bug fix: rewrote all four same-file calls from `from MemoryCore`
        to the canonical no-module form.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Four sequential predicates. Short-circuits on the first failure.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Composite validation gives the strongest single-call assurance
        this module can provide for a raw pointer. It does not check
        liveness in the layout registry; pair with primitives/memory/
        layout.runa for that.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Check null pointer (same-file call)
    Let null_check be proc memory_check_null_dereference with ptr
    If null_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check pointer range (same-file call)
    Let range_check be proc memory_check_pointer_range with ptr, size
    If range_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check alignment (same-file call)
    Let align_check be proc memory_check_alignment with ptr, MEMORY_ALIGNMENT_DEFAULT
    If align_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check corruption (same-file call)
    Let corruption_check be proc memory_check_corruption with ptr, size
    If corruption_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1  Note: All checks passed
End Process

Process called "memory_safety_report" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Diagnostic entry point that returns a specific error code instead
        of a boolean, so callers writing logs / error reports can record
        the precise reason a pointer was rejected. Distinguishes
        null-dereference, invalid-range, and corruption as separate
        outcomes; the success path returns MEMORY_SAFETY_SUCCESS.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. ptr == 0 -> MEMORY_SAFETY_NULL_DEREFERENCE.
            2. memory_check_pointer_range(ptr, size) - if 0 ->
               MEMORY_SAFETY_INVALID_PTR.
            3. memory_check_corruption(ptr, size) - if 0 ->
               MEMORY_SAFETY_CORRUPTION.
            4. Return MEMORY_SAFETY_SUCCESS.

        Bug fix: rewrote both same-file calls from `from MemoryCore` to
        the canonical no-module form.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Returning a specific error code (negative integer) instead of a
        boolean lets the caller correlate failures with the failing
        predicate, which is useful in security telemetry and incident
        analysis. The constants are stable - downstream tooling can rely
        on the numeric values.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return MEMORY_SAFETY_NULL_DEREFERENCE
    End If

    Note: Same-file call
    Let range_check be proc memory_check_pointer_range with ptr, size
    If range_check is equal to 0:
        Return MEMORY_SAFETY_INVALID_PTR
    End If

    Note: Same-file call
    Let corruption_check be proc memory_check_corruption with ptr, size
    If corruption_check is equal to 0:
        Return MEMORY_SAFETY_CORRUPTION
    End If

    Return MEMORY_SAFETY_SUCCESS
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Memory Safety Complete - Runtime Memory Validation Surface
============================================================================
:End Note
